      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "**1.What is NumPy, and why is it widely used in Python?**"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "jCEKdwbOH4LT"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "**What is NumPy?**\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "NumPy (Numerical Python) is a fundamental library in Python for numerical computing. It provides support for large, multi-dimensional arrays and matrices, along with a vast collection of high-level mathematical functions to operate on these arrays efficiently.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Why is NumPy Widely Used in Python?**\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "1.Efficient Data Structures:\n",
        "\n",
        "- N-Dimensional Arrays: The ndarray provided by NumPy is a highly optimized data structure for storing and performing operations on large datasets.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- Compact and memory-efficient compared to Python lists.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "2.Performance:\n",
        "\n",
        "- NumPy is implemented in C, making it much faster than standard Python lists for numerical operations.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- Supports vectorized operations, allowing for element-wise computations without explicit loops.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "3.Rich Functionality:\n",
        "\n",
        "- Wide range of built-in functions for linear algebra, statistics, Fourier transforms, and more.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- Broadcasting capabilities allow operations on arrays of different shapes without additional memory overhead.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "4.Integration with Other Libraries:\n",
        "\n",
        "- Many scientific and machine learning libraries, like SciPy, pandas, scikit-learn, TensorFlow, and PyTorch, are built on top of NumPy or integrate with it seamlessly.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "5.Ease of Use:\n",
        "\n",
        "- Simple and intuitive syntax for performing complex numerical operations.\n",
        "Functions like slicing, reshaping, and aggregations make data manipulation straightforward.\n",
        "\n",
        "6.Open Source and Well-Supported:\n",
        "\n",
        "- Open-source library with extensive documentation and a large, active community.\n",
        "\n",
        "- Regular updates and compatibility with other Python scientific computing tools.\n"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "9kpShIEkIFkP"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "**2. How does broadcasting work in NumPy?**"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "azq38dfqI8Yp"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "Broadcasting in NumPy refers to a mechanism that allows operations on arrays of different shapes by automatically expanding their dimensions, so the shapes are compatible without the need for explicit replication of data.\n",
        "\n",
        "This makes operations between arrays of different sizes efficient, both in terms of memory usage and computation time.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Rules of Broadcasting**\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "1.Alignment of Dimensions:\n",
        "\n",
        "- NumPy compares the shapes of two arrays element by element, starting from the rightmost dimension.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "2.Compatibility:\n",
        "\n",
        "- Two dimensions are considered compatible if:\n",
        "- They are equal, or\n",
        "- One of them is 1.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "3.Expansion:\n",
        "\n",
        "- If a dimension is 1 or absent in one of the arrays, it is virtually expanded (broadcast) to match the other array's size.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "4.Resulting Shape:\n",
        "\n",
        "- The resulting array's shape is the maximum size along each dimension."
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "otH21H9WJFS_"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "**3.What is a Pandas DataFrame?**\n"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "55ZIcMZwKCzV"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "A Pandas DataFrame is a two-dimensional, labeled data structure in the Pandas library, akin to a spreadsheet or a SQL table, but much more powerful. It is one of the most widely used structures in Python for handling and analyzing structured data.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "**Key Features of a DataFrame**\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "1.Tabular Data Representation:\n",
        "\n",
        "- Organized as rows and columns, where each column can have a different data type (e.g., integers, floats, strings).\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "2.Labeled Index and Columns:\n",
        "\n",
        "- Rows are labeled with an index.\n",
        "- Columns have descriptive names, making data easy to access and manipulate.\n",
        "\n",
        "3.Flexible and Heterogeneous:\n",
        "\n",
        "- Can store heterogeneous data types, such as numeric, categorical, and string data in a single structure.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "4.Data Alignment:\n",
        "\n",
        "- Operations automatically align on row and column labels.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "5.Powerful Tools:\n",
        "\n",
        "- Provides built-in methods for data manipulation, aggregation, filtering, and visualization."
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "A0kKRG2RKQD-"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "**4.Explain the use of the groupby() method in Pandas?**"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "IJkw39NGLDgN"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "The groupby() method in Pandas is a powerful tool used to split data into groups based on some criteria, apply a function or computation on each group, and then combine the results into a single DataFrame or Series. It is commonly used for data aggregation, transformation, and analysis.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "**Workflow of groupby()**\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "The groupby() method follows a split-apply-combine process:\n",
        "\n",
        "1.Split: The data is split into groups based on specified criteria (e.g., column values).\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "2.Apply: A function (e.g., aggregation, transformation) is applied to each group.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "3.Combine: The results of the applied function are combined into a new DataFrame or Series.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "**Examples**\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "1. Basic Grouping and Aggregation\n"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "Gg9AGvN1LDc0"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": [
        "import pandas as pd\n",
        "\n",
        "# Sample data\n",
        "data = {\n",
        "    'Category': ['A', 'B', 'A', 'B', 'A'],\n",
        "    'Values': [10, 20, 30, 40, 50]\n",
        "}\n",
        "df = pd.DataFrame(data)\n",
        "\n",
        "# Group by 'Category' and calculate the sum of 'Values'\n",
        "grouped = df.groupby('Category')['Values'].sum()\n",
        "\n",
        "print(grouped)\n"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "colab": {
          "base_uri": "https://localhost:8080/"
        },
        "id": "-ySRIs6K7UIy",
        "outputId": "8b05c6f2-3ac0-49ce-fd13-ba4e4412d520"
      },
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": [
        {
          "output_type": "stream",
          "name": "stdout",
          "text": [
            "Category\n",
            "A    90\n",
            "B    60\n",
            "Name: Values, dtype: int64\n"
          ]
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "2. Grouping Multiple Columns"

      "metadata": {
        "id": "Tjl4pWMDMEBq"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": [
        "# Group by multiple columns and compute the mean\n",
        "grouped = df.groupby(['Category', 'Values']).size()\n",
        "\n",
        "print(grouped)\n"
      ],

      "cell_type": "markdown",

        "3. Applying Custom Functions"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "N0gZRbxVMPAC"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": [
        "# Apply a custom function to each group\n",
        "grouped = df.groupby('Category')['Values'].apply(lambda x: x.max() - x.min())\n",
        "\n",
        "print(grouped)\n"
      ],

      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "4. Transforming Data Within Groups\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "The transform() method can apply a function to each group and return a DataFrame of the same size."
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "JqDJwshHMhpO"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": [
        "df['Normalized'] = df.groupby('Category')['Values'].transform(lambda x: x / x.sum())\n",
        "\n",
        "print(df)\n"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "colab": {
          "base_uri": "https://localhost:8080/"

        "5. Iterating Over Groups"

      "metadata": {
        "id": "l66qlWU4MoQY"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": [
        "# Iterate through groups\n",
        "for name, group in df.groupby('Category'):\n",
        "    print(f\"Group: {name}\")\n",
        "    print(group)\n"
      ],
      "metadata": {

            "3        B      40    0.666667\n"
          ]
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "**Common Aggregation Methods**\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- sum(): Sum of values in each group.\n",
        "- mean(): Mean of values in each group.\n",
        "- count(): Number of non-NA values in each group.\n",
        "- max()/min(): Maximum/minimum values in each group.\n",
        "- std(): Standard deviation of each group.\n",
        "- size(): Number of elements in each group.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "**Practical Use Cases**\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "1.Sales Analysis: Group sales data by region or product to calculate total or average sales.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "2.Customer Segmentation: Group customers by demographics or purchasing behavior for insights.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "3.Data Cleaning: Identify and address missing or outlier data within specific groups.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "4.Experiment Analysis: Analyze results by experimental groups.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "The groupby() method is indispensable for analyzing and summarizing large datasets efficiently!"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "1GhbvTlJM6H9"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "**5.Why is Seaborn preferred for statistical visualizations?**"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "47vuo5KYNRdK"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "Seaborn is preferred for statistical visualizations because it provides a high-level interface for creating visually attractive and informative graphics that are particularly suited for exploring and understanding relationships in data. Hereâ€™s why Seaborn is widely favored:\n",
        "\n",
        "**Key Advantages of Seaborn**\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "1.Built-in Support for Statistical Visualizations:\n",
        "\n",
        "- Seaborn includes functions specifically designed for statistical analysis, such as regression plots, categorical plots, and distribution visualizations.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- Example: sns.regplot() provides regression lines with confidence intervals.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "2.Ease of Use:\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "Simple and intuitive API for creating complex visualizations with minimal code.\n",
        "Handles tasks like color mapping, faceting, and legend creation automatically.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "3.Beautiful Aesthetics:\n",
        "\n",
        "- Seaborn comes with built-in themes (e.g., darkgrid, whitegrid) that produce visually appealing plots by default.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- Supports customization for enhanced readability.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "4.Integration with Pandas:\n",
        "\n",
        "- Works seamlessly with Pandas DataFrames, allowing direct use of column names for plotting without additional data preparation.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "5.Advanced Categorical Plotting:\n",
        "\n",
        "- Provides specialized functions for visualizing categorical data, such as sns.boxplot(), sns.violinplot(), sns.barplot(), and sns.catplot().\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "6.Data-Aware Functions:\n",
        "\n",
        "- Automatically calculates and plots statistical summaries (e.g., means, medians) in certain plot types, such as sns.barplot().\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "7.Built-in Aggregation:\n",
        "\n",
        "- Many functions allow automatic aggregation of data, eliminating the need for preprocessing. For example, sns.barplot() computes means and confidence intervals.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "8.Faceting for Subplots:\n",
        "\n",
        "- The FacetGrid class and functions like sns.catplot() allow easy creation of complex subplot layouts for multi-variable analysis.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "9.Rich Support for Distributions:\n",
        "\n",
        "- Functions like sns.histplot(), sns.kdeplot(), and sns.jointplot() are tailored for visualizing univariate and bivariate distributions.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "10.Statistical Inference:\n",
        "\n",
        "- Confidence intervals and error bars are included by default in many plot types, aiding in visual statistical inference.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "11.Customization and Control:\n",
        "\n",
        "- Offers fine-grained control over plot elements, such as colors, markers, and styles.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "**Example Visualizations in Seaborn**\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "1. Correlation Heatmap\n"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "0LE1B8RPN53N"

        "})\n",
        "\n",
        "sns.heatmap(data.corr(), annot=True, cmap='coolwarm')\n",

      "source": [
        "**6.What are the differences between NumPy arrays and Python lists?**"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "OgfkesD8VLdD"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "NumPy arrays and Python lists are both used to store collections of data, but they have significant differences in terms of functionality, performance, and use cases. Hereâ€™s a comparison:\n",
        "\n",
        "**1. Data Type**\n",
        "\n",
        "- Python Lists: Can store elements of different data types (e.g., integers, strings, floats).\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- NumPy Arrays: Require all elements to be of the same data type, which is enforced for performance optimization.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "**2. Performance**\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- Python Lists: Slower because they are dynamically typed and not optimized for numerical operations.\n",
        "\n",
        "- NumPy Arrays: Faster for numerical computations due to optimized C and Fortran code under the hood.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "**3. Memory Efficiency**\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- Python Lists: Less memory efficient because they store additional metadata for each element.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- NumPy Arrays: More memory efficient as they use a contiguous block of memory with a fixed data type.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "**4. Operations**\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- Python Lists: Require loops or list comprehensions for element-wise operations, which can be verbose and slow.\n",
        "\n",
        "- NumPy Arrays: Support vectorized operations (e.g., element-wise addition, multiplication) directly, which are concise and efficient.\n",
        "\n",
        "**5. Multi-dimensional Data**\n",
        "\n",
        "- Python Lists: Support nested lists to mimic multi-dimensional arrays, but operations are cumbersome.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- NumPy Arrays: Provide built-in support for multi-dimensional arrays with functionality for slicing, reshaping, and broadcasting.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "**6. Built-in Methods**\n",
        "\n",
        "- Python Lists: Limited built-in functionality for numerical operations.\n",
        "\n",
        "- NumPy Arrays: Extensive mathematical and statistical operations, such as mean, sum, and linear algebra methods.\n",
        "\n",
        "**7. Indexing and Slicing**\n",
        "\n",
        "- Python Lists: Support basic indexing and slicing.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- NumPy Arrays: Allow advanced slicing, including boolean indexing, fancy indexing, and multidimensional slicing.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "**8. Libraries and Ecosystem**\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- Python Lists: General-purpose and not specialized for numerical computing.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- NumPy Arrays: Integrated with many libraries like pandas, SciPy, and TensorFlow, making them essential for scientific computing and machine learning.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "**9. Broadcasting**\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- Python Lists: Do not support broadcasting.\n",
        "\n",
        "- NumPy Arrays: Support broadcasting, which enables operations between arrays of different shapes."
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "s1nGT8GGYSJP"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "**7.What is a heatmap, and when should it be used?**"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "dhOFOa_vZ-o1"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "**What is a Heatmap?**\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "A heatmap is a graphical representation of data where individual values are represented as colors. It provides a visual summary of information, making it easier to identify patterns, trends, and outliers in large datasets.\n",
        "\n",
        "The data in a heatmap is typically arranged in a grid-like structure, with rows and columns corresponding to specific categories, variables, or time intervals. The intensity or shade of the color indicates the magnitude or frequency of the data points.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Types of Heatmaps**\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "1.Quantitative Heatmaps: Represent numerical data, such as correlation matrices or temperature distributions.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "2.Categorical Heatmaps: Use colors to represent categories or classes in a dataset.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "3.Geographical Heatmaps: Show data intensity or distribution over a map, like population density or weather patterns.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "**When to Use a Heatmap**\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "Heatmaps are particularly useful in the following scenarios:\n",
        "\n",
        "1.Analyzing Correlation or Relationships:\n",
        "\n",
        "- Ideal for visualizing correlation matrices to identify relationships between variables in a dataset.\n",
        "\n",
        "- Example: Understanding which features in a dataset are highly correlated.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "2.Exploring Patterns and Trends:\n",
        "\n",
        "- Use heatmaps to observe patterns or anomalies in time-series data or other datasets.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- Example: Visualizing website traffic over hours of the day and days of the week.\n",
        "\n",
        "3.Summarizing Large Datasets:\n",
        "\n",
        "- Useful for summarizing complex datasets in a concise visual format.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- Example: Displaying the performance of a machine learning model across different parameters.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "4.Detecting Outliers:\n",
        "\n",
        "- Easy identification of outliers in datasets where numerical values deviate significantly from the norm.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- Example: Finding regions with extreme temperatures in weather data.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "5.Comparing Data Across Categories:\n",
        "\n",
        "- Effective for comparing the magnitude of different values across categories.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- Example: Visualizing sales figures across products and regions.\n",
        "\n",
        "6.Geographical Visualization:\n",
        "\n",
        "- Commonly used for spatial data to show the intensity of a variable over a geographical area.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- Example: Mapping COVID-19 infection rates across different regions.\n"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "KI9UZ4rVaSij"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "**8.What does the term â€œvectorized operationâ€ mean in NumPy?**"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "iJIQdpgRb05f"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "**Vectorized Operation in NumPy**\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "A vectorized operation in NumPy refers to performing operations on entire arrays (or large chunks of data) at once, without the need for explicit loops. These operations leverage low-level optimizations written in C, enabling faster computation and more concise code.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Key Characteristics of Vectorized Operations**\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "1.Element-wise Execution:\n",
        "\n",
        "- Operations are applied simultaneously to all elements of the array.\n",
        "\n",
        "- Example: Adding two arrays, multiplying elements by a scalar, or applying mathematical functions like sine or exponential.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "2.No Explicit Loops:\n",
        "\n",
        "- Unlike traditional Python loops, vectorized operations are written in a single expression.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- This reduces boilerplate code and makes the program more readable.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "3.Optimized Performance:\n",
        "\n",
        "- Vectorized operations are faster than loops because they use optimized, low-level implementations and take advantage of CPU parallelism.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "4.Broadcasting:\n",
        "\n",
        "- Operations can be performed on arrays of different shapes using broadcasting rules.\n",
        "\n",
        "- Example: Adding a scalar to a 2D array.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "**Examples of Vectorized Operations**\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "1. Arithmetic Operations"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "5tROy2wzcN1N"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": [
        "import numpy as np\n",
        "\n",
        "# Creating arrays\n",
        "arr1 = np.array([1, 2, 3])\n",
        "arr2 = np.array([4, 5, 6])\n",
        "\n",
        "# Element-wise addition\n",
        "result = arr1 + arr2  # [5, 7, 9]\n",
        "\n",
        "# Scalar multiplication\n",
        "scaled = arr1 * 2  # [2, 4, 6]\n"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "DQ_Le_4iPW2l"

    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "**9. How does Matplotlib differ from Plotly?**"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "N6HWn07PfNSr"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "Matplotlib and Plotly are both popular Python libraries for data visualization, but they differ significantly in features, usage, and strengths. Here's a detailed comparison:\n",
        "\n",
        "**1. Nature of the Library**\n",
        "\n",
        "- Matplotlib:\n",
        "\n",
        "- A static plotting library focused on creating publication-quality plots.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- Generates static images like PNG, JPG, or PDF.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- Offers extensive customization but often requires more effort for complex visualizations.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- Ideal for simple or detailed plots in research or academic settings.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- Plotly:\n",
        "\n",
        "- A library for creating interactive, web-based visualizations.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- Generates interactive plots in HTML format, viewable in web browsers.\n",
        "\n",
        "- Built for modern data storytelling and dashboards.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- Ideal for presentations, exploratory analysis, or applications requiring user interaction.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "**2. Interactivity**\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- Matplotlib:\n",
        "\n",
        "- Primarily static plots, but some limited interactivity is possible using tools like widgets (matplotlib.widgets) or mpl_interactions.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- Requires additional libraries like mpld3 or bokeh for web-based interactivity.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- Plotly:\n",
        "\n",
        "- Natively supports interactivity out of the box (zoom, pan, hover, etc.).\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- Advanced interactive features like sliders, dropdowns, and animations are easy to implement.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "**3. Ease of Use**\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- Matplotlib:\n",
        "\n",
        "- Offers detailed control but has a steeper learning curve for complex plots.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- Requires manual adjustments for formatting and styling.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- Plotly:\n",
        "\n",
        "- User-friendly and designed for ease of use, especially for creating interactive plots.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- Built-in styles and themes simplify customization.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "**4. Visualization Types**\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- Matplotlib:\n",
        "\n",
        "- Supports a wide range of static plots: line plots, scatter plots, bar charts, histograms, etc.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- Extensions like seaborn provide advanced visualizations (e.g., heatmaps, violin plots).\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- Plotly:\n",
        "\n",
        "- Supports a similar range of plots but also excels at interactive 3D plots, geographic maps, and animations.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- Includes specialized visualizations for time-series data, choropleths, and financial charts.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "**5. Ecosystem and Integration**\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- Matplotlib:\n",
        "\n",
        "- Well-integrated with scientific computing libraries like NumPy and pandas.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- Often used in conjunction with Jupyter Notebooks and tools like Seaborn.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- Plotly:\n",
        "\n",
        "- Works seamlessly with pandas, NumPy, and other data analysis libraries.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- Can integrate into web applications using frameworks like Flask and Dash (a Plotly product).\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "**6. Customization**\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- Matplotlib:\n",
        "\n",
        "- Extremely customizable, allowing granular control over every aspect of a plot (axes, ticks, labels, colors).\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- Customization requires more effort compared to Plotly.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- Plotly:\n",
        "\n",
        "- Provides powerful yet straightforward customization options.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- Themes and presets make it easy to create visually appealing plots without deep customization.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "**7. Output**\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- Matplotlib:\n",
        "\n",
        "- Outputs static images in formats like PNG, PDF, and SVG.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- Less suited for interactive or web-based visualizations.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- Plotly:\n",
        "\n",
        "- Outputs interactive plots in HTML, easily embeddable in web pages or dashboards.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- Can also export static images if needed.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "**8. Use Cases**\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- Matplotlib:\n",
        "\n",
        "- Best for academic papers, static reports, and when fine-tuning every detail is necessary.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- Example: A detailed scatter plot for a scientific paper.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- Plotly:\n",
        "\n",
        "- Best for presentations, dashboards, and exploratory data analysis requiring interactivity.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- Example: An interactive sales dashboard with filters and real-time updates.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "**9. Performance**\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- Matplotlib:\n",
        "\n",
        "- Suitable for small to medium datasets.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- May struggle with performance when visualizing very large datasets.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- Plotly:\n",
        "\n",
        "- Handles large datasets more efficiently, especially in interactive visualizations.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- Offers specialized tools like WebGL rendering for high-performance plots.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "**Example Comparison**\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "**Matplotlib Plot**"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "6i5pfS5Ugop7"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": [

        "\n",

        "plt.title(\"Matplotlib Example\")\n",
        "plt.xlabel(\"X-axis\")\n",

    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "**10.What is the significance of hierarchical indexing in Pandas?**"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "48W-McAOlCD-"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "**Significance of Hierarchical Indexing in Pandas**\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "Hierarchical indexing, also known as a MultiIndex, is a powerful feature in pandas that allows you to work with higher-dimensional data in a lower-dimensional data structure, such as a Series or DataFrame. It is particularly useful for organizing and analyzing data with multiple levels of categorical information.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "**Key Features of Hierarchical Indexing**\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "1.Multi-level Indexing:\n",
        "\n",
        "- Enables rows and/or columns to have multiple levels (or tiers) of indices.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- Example: Indexing by year and month, or by region and product category.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "2.Improved Organization:\n",
        "\n",
        "- Allows for logical organization of data with hierarchical relationships.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- Example: Sales data grouped by region, then by city.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "3.Facilitates Aggregation and Grouping:\n",
        "\n",
        "- Simplifies grouping, reshaping, and performing operations on grouped data.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- Example: Aggregating sales data by region and year.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "4.Efficient Slicing and Subsetting:\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- Provides intuitive ways to slice and subset data using multiple index levels.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- Example: Selecting all data for a specific region or year.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "5.Flexibility in Reshaping:\n",
        "\n",
        "- Enables pivoting, stacking, and unstacking data easily.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- Example: Converting a long-format DataFrame into a wide format and vice versa.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "**Supports Complex Relationships:**\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- Useful when dealing with datasets that have nested or hierarchical structures.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- Example: Time-series data with different resolutions (year, month, day).\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "**When to Use Hierarchical Indexing**\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- When data naturally has multiple levels of categorization.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- To simplify the representation of higher-dimensional data.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- To perform operations that require grouping or hierarchical organization.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- To analyze relationships between multiple categorical variables.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "**Examples of Hierarchical Indexing**\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "1. Creating a MultiIndex\n"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "VUbMPIJ0lVHC"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": [
        "import pandas as pd\n",
        "import numpy as np\n",
        "\n",
        "# Define MultiIndex\n",
        "arrays = [\n",
        "    ['Region1', 'Region1', 'Region2', 'Region2'],\n",
        "    ['ProductA', 'ProductB', 'ProductA', 'ProductB']\n",
        "]\n",
        "index = pd.MultiIndex.from_arrays(arrays, names=['Region', 'Product'])\n",
        "\n",
        "# Create DataFrame\n",
        "data = pd.DataFrame({'Sales': [100, 200, 150, 300]}, index=index)\n",
        "print(data)\n"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "colab": {
          "base_uri": "https://localhost:8080/"

      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "**11.What is the role of Seabornâ€™s pairplot() function?**"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "baEFsW3Gmn6I"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "**Role of Seaborn's pairplot() Function**\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "Seabornâ€™s pairplot() is a powerful tool for exploratory data analysis. It creates a grid of scatter plots (or other visualizations) for examining relationships between numerical variables in a dataset. The primary role of pairplot() is to help identify trends, correlations, and patterns among variables, as well as distributions of individual variables.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Key Features of pairplot()**\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "1.Pairwise Scatter Plots:\n",
        "\n",
        "- Displays scatter plots for every combination of numerical variables in the dataset.\n",
        "\n",
        "-Helps identify potential correlations or relationships between variables.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "2.Diagonal Plots:\n",
        "\n",
        "- Displays univariate distributions of each variable on the diagonal of the grid (by default, histograms or kernel density plots).\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "3.Hue Parameter:\n",
        "\n",
        "- Adds another dimension by categorizing data points based on a categorical variable.\n",
        "\n",
        "- Different hues (colors) represent different categories.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "4.Customizable Aesthetics:\n",
        "\n",
        "- Options for customizing markers, palettes, and kinds of plots (e.g., scatter, KDE).\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "5.Facilitates Quick Analysis:\n",
        "\n",
        "- Allows rapid exploration of relationships and patterns in a dataset without requiring detailed coding.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "**When to Use pairplot()**\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "1.To visualize relationships between numerical variables.\n",
        "\n",
        "2.To explore clusters or groups in data based on a categorical feature (using hue).\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "3.To detect correlations, outliers, or trends.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "4.To compare distributions of numerical variables.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "5.During exploratory data analysis (EDA) to gain insights into the data structure.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "**Example Usage**\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "1. Basic Pairplot\n"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "Z-zgbdhNm91K"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": [

        "\n",
        "# Load example dataset\n",
        "data = sns.load_dataset('iris')\n",
        "\n",
        "# Create a pairplot\n",
        "sns.pairplot(data)\n",
        "plt.show()\n"
      ],

      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "**12.What is the purpose of the describe() function in Pandas?**"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "LeFyzmkXomoz"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "The describe() function in pandas is a versatile tool used to generate a summary of key statistics for numerical or categorical columns in a DataFrame or Series. It provides a quick overview of the distribution, central tendency, dispersion, and count of the data.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Purpose of describe()**\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "1.Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA):\n",
        "\n",
        "- Quickly assess the structure and quality of the dataset.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- Identify potential issues like missing values, outliers, or unexpected data ranges.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "2.Summarization of Data:\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- Offers a concise summary of key statistical metrics for numerical columns.\n",
        "\n",
        "- For categorical data, provides information like counts and unique values.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "3.Insight into Data Distribution:\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- Helps understand the spread, central tendencies, and variability of the data.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "**Behavior of describe()**\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "1.Numerical Columns:\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- By default, it calculates the following statistics for numeric data:\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- Count: Number of non-missing values.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- Mean: Average value.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- Standard Deviation (std): Measures dispersion around the mean.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- Min and Max: Minimum and maximum values.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- Quartiles: 25th percentile (25%), median (50%), and 75th percentile (75%).\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "2.Categorical Columns:\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- If applied to non-numerical (categorical or object) data:\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "2.Count: Number of non-missing values.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "3.Unique: Number of unique categories.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "4.Top: Most frequent category.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "5.Freq: Frequency of the top category.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "3.Custom Inclusion:\n",
        "\n",
        "- Allows summarization of all columns (include='all') or specific data types using the include and exclude parameters.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "**Examples**\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "1. Default Behavior with Numerical Data"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "M5JBKVDwo0gX"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": [
        "import pandas as pd\n",
        "\n",
        "# Example DataFrame\n",
        "data = {\n",
        "    'Age': [25, 30, 35, 40, 45],\n",
        "    'Salary': [50000, 60000, 70000, 80000, 90000]\n",
        "}\n",
        "df = pd.DataFrame(data)\n",
        "\n",
        "# Summary statistics\n",
        "print(df.describe())\n"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "colab": {
          "base_uri": "https://localhost:8080/"
        },
        "id": "vn9xBO-Soe1v",
        "outputId": "54b2ebb8-585d-4fdc-90e8-c371d558ba07"
      },
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": [
        {
          "output_type": "stream",
          "name": "stdout",
          "text": [
            "             Age        Salary\n",
            "count   5.000000      5.000000\n",
            "mean   35.000000  70000.000000\n",
            "std     7.905694  15811.388301\n",
            "min    25.000000  50000.000000\n",
            "25%    30.000000  60000.000000\n",
            "50%    35.000000  70000.000000\n",
            "75%    40.000000  80000.000000\n",
            "max    45.000000  90000.000000\n"

        }
      ]

    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "**13.Why is handling missing data important in Pandas?**"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "3cztbOevqSna"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "**Importance of Handling Missing Data in Pandas**\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "Handling missing data is a crucial step in data analysis and preprocessing because missing values can significantly impact the quality, reliability, and accuracy of your analysis and machine learning models. Pandas provides robust tools for identifying, handling, and imputing missing data, ensuring that the dataset is clean and ready for further processing.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Key Reasons for Handling Missing Data**\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "1. Avoiding Errors in Analysis\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- Missing data can cause errors or unexpected results during calculations, statistical analyses, or data visualizations.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- Operations like mean, median, and correlation calculations can yield incorrect results if missing values are present.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "**2. Improving Model Performance**\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- Machine learning models cannot handle missing values directly in most cases.\n",
        "Handling missing data appropriately ensures that models receive complete and meaningful input, improving their accuracy and robustness.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "**3. Ensuring Consistent Dataset Dimensions**\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- Missing values can disrupt the structure of the dataset, leading to misaligned rows or columns.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- Proper handling preserves the integrity of the data structure.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "**4. Retaining Valuable Information**\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- Thoughtless removal of rows or columns with missing data may lead to the loss of important information.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- Careful handling ensures that the dataset retains as much useful information as possible.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "**5. Enhancing Data Quality**\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- Missing data can signal issues like errors in data collection, storage, or entry.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- Addressing missing values improves the overall quality and reliability of the dataset.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "**6. Avoiding Biased Results**\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- Ignoring or improperly handling missing data can introduce biases.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- For example, removing rows with missing values might disproportionately affect certain groups or categories, leading to skewed analysis.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "**Methods for Handling Missing Data in Pandas**\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",

        "**Benefits of Using Plotly for Data Visualization**\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "Plotly is a powerful, flexible, and user-friendly library for creating interactive and visually appealing data visualizations. Its robust functionality makes it a popular choice for data analysts, scientists, and developers across various domains.\n",
        "\n",
        "**1. Interactivity**\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- Dynamic Features: Zooming, panning, hovering, and tooltips are built into Plotly's visualizations.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- Interactive Exploration: Allows users to interact with data in real-time, facilitating deeper insights.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "-Custom Callbacks: Advanced interactivity through custom callbacks and event handling in Plotly Dash.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "**2. Versatility**\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- Wide Range of Chart Types: Supports scatter plots, line plots, bar charts, pie charts, heatmaps, 3D plots, geographical maps, and more.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- Suitability for Various Domains: Used in finance, healthcare, engineering, and social sciences for diverse data visualization needs.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "**3. High-Quality Visualizations**\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- Aesthetic Designs: Produces publication-quality and highly customizable plots.\n",

        "\n",
        "\n",
        "**4. Ease of Use**\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- Simple API: Intuitive and straightforward API, making it easy to create complex visualizations with minimal code.\n",

        "\n",
        "\n",
        "**5. Support for Big Data**\n",

        "\n",

        "\n",

        "\n",

        "**8. Customization**\n",

        "\n",
        "- Growing Community: Active community and comprehensive documentation.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- Third-Party Integrations: Works with other libraries like Pandas, NumPy, and Matplotlib for seamless workflows.\n"

        "**15.How does NumPy handle multidimensional arrays?**"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "s46Nrlp8vRVw"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "**How NumPy Handles Multidimensional Arrays**\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "NumPy excels at working with multidimensional arrays, also called ndarrays. These arrays are central to NumPy and allow efficient storage, manipulation, and computation of data in multiple dimensions. Hereâ€™s an overview of how NumPy manages and operates on multidimensional arrays:\n",
        "\n",
        "1. Multidimensional Array Representation\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- A NumPy array (ndarray) can have one or more dimensions:\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- 1D array: A simple list-like structure.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- 2D array: A matrix-like structure with rows and columns.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- nD array: Extends to higher dimensions, such as 3D tensors or beyond.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Example:**"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "-3hEzGUOwXN_"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": [
        "import numpy as np\n",
        "\n",
        "# 1D array\n",
        "array_1d = np.array([1, 2, 3])\n",
        "\n",
        "# 2D array\n",
        "array_2d = np.array([[1, 2], [3, 4]])\n",
        "\n",
        "# 3D array\n",
        "array_3d = np.array([[[1, 2], [3, 4]], [[5, 6], [7, 8]]])\n",
        "\n",
        "print(array_1d.shape)  # Output: (3,)\n",
        "print(array_2d.shape)  # Output: (2, 2)\n",
        "print(array_3d.shape)  # Output: (2, 2, 2)\n"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "colab": {
          "base_uri": "https://localhost:8080/"
        },
        "id": "2-5hIxDftlBL",
        "outputId": "cfca80a9-d01f-42bd-f299-6eaf101758d0"
      },
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": [
        {
          "output_type": "stream",
          "name": "stdout",
          "text": [
            "(3,)\n",
            "(2, 2)\n",
            "(2, 2, 2)\n"
          ]
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "**2. Shape and Dimensionality**\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- ndarray.shape: A tuple representing the size of the array along each dimension.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- ndarray.ndim: Returns the number of dimensions (rank) of the array.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "**Example:**"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "tfeKogevwuKE"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": [
        "print(array_2d.shape)  # Output: (2, 2)\n",
        "print(array_2d.ndim)   # Output: 2\n"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "colab": {
          "base_uri": "https://localhost:8080/"
        },
        "id": "x-v8VB5Pwpmm",
        "outputId": "dbdb2dca-fae8-4e62-b300-4586745d7975"
      },
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": [
        {
          "output_type": "stream",
          "name": "stdout",
          "text": [
            "(2, 2)\n",
            "2\n"
          ]
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "**3. Indexing and Slicing**\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "NumPy allows efficient indexing and slicing for multidimensional arrays:\n",
        "\n",
        "- Indexing: Access specific elements using indices.\n",
        "\n",
        "- Slicing: Access subarrays using ranges for each dimension.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Example:**"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "8bXbNA_DxMXp"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": [
        "# 2D array indexing\n",
        "print(array_2d[0, 1])  # Output: 2 (element at row 0, column 1)\n",
        "\n",
        "# 2D array slicing\n",
        "print(array_2d[:, 1])  # Output: [2, 4] (all rows, column 1)\n",
        "\n",
        "# 3D array slicing\n",
        "print(array_3d[1, :, 0])  # Output: [5, 7] (all rows of the second matrix, first column)\n"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "colab": {
          "base_uri": "https://localhost:8080/"
        },
        "id": "8uzmc8Wqw5Z4",
        "outputId": "88fc4c02-5adc-4eb2-da61-a970761517bf"
      },
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": [
        {
          "output_type": "stream",
          "name": "stdout",
          "text": [
            "2\n",
            "[2 4]\n",
            "[5 7]\n"
          ]
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "**4. Broadcasting**\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "NumPy supports broadcasting, enabling arithmetic operations between arrays of different shapes in a memory-efficient manner.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Example:**"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "GTNXkYWbxZPM"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": [
        "a = np.array([[1, 2, 3]])\n",
        "b = np.array([[1], [2], [3]])\n",
        "\n",
        "# Broadcasting adds the 1D array to each row of the 2D array\n",
        "result = a + b\n",
        "print(result)\n",
        "# Output:\n",
        "# [[2 3 4]\n",
        "#  [3 4 5]\n",
        "#  [4 5 6]]\n"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "colab": {
          "base_uri": "https://localhost:8080/"
        },
        "id": "6jI3vI6IxYBQ",
        "outputId": "45c917db-7e94-467c-99b5-978deb31b21e"
      },
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": [
        {
          "output_type": "stream",
          "name": "stdout",
          "text": [
            "[[2 3 4]\n",
            " [3 4 5]\n",
            " [4 5 6]]\n"
          ]
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "**5. Universal Functions (ufuncs)**\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "NumPyâ€™s ufuncs operate element-wise on multidimensional arrays, enabling efficient computations.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Example:**"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "DwgFO8CIxnQh"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": [
        "# Applying a ufunc (sin) on a 2D array\n",
        "result = np.sin(array_2d)\n",
        "print(result)\n"
      ],
      "metadata": {

          "base_uri": "https://localhost:8080/"

    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "**6. Reshaping and Transposing**\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- reshape(): Change the shape of an array without modifying its data.\n",
        "\n",
        "- transpose() / .T: Flip dimensions of the array.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "**Example:**"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "L2X-JRMIx46z"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": [
        "# Reshaping a 1D array into a 2D array\n",
        "reshaped = array_1d.reshape((1, 3))\n",
        "print(reshaped)  # Output: [[1 2 3]]\n",
        "\n",
        "# Transposing a 2D array\n",
        "transposed = array_2d.T\n",
        "print(transposed)\n",
        "# Output:\n",
        "# [[1 3]\n",
        "#  [2 4]]\n"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "colab": {
          "base_uri": "https://localhost:8080/"
        },
        "id": "QMJup5n-xs8K",
        "outputId": "add54e98-6432-45c2-d0a7-7df0faca48db"
      },
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": [
        {
          "output_type": "stream",
          "name": "stdout",
          "text": [
            "[[1 2 3]]\n",
            "[[1 3]\n",
            " [2 4]]\n"
          ]
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "**7. Memory Efficiency**\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- NumPy arrays are stored as contiguous blocks in memory, allowing for efficient computations.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- Operations on multidimensional arrays are vectorized, avoiding the need for Python loops.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "**8. Aggregation Functions**\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- NumPy provides aggregation functions like sum, mean, and max that work efficiently on multidimensional arrays along specific axes.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Example:**"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "JnkgekSRyFnw"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": [
        "# Sum along rows (axis 1)\n",
        "print(array_2d.sum(axis=1))  # Output: [3, 7]\n",
        "\n",
        "# Mean along columns (axis 0)\n",
        "print(array_2d.mean(axis=0))  # Output: [2. 3.]\n"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "colab": {
          "base_uri": "https://localhost:8080/"
        },
        "id": "eLbXBcTdyBxR",
        "outputId": "befbc263-4274-4ef1-e105-f6725d6af106"
      },
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": [
        {
          "output_type": "stream",
          "name": "stdout",
          "text": [
            "[3 7]\n",
            "[2. 3.]\n"
          ]
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "**9. Advanced Indexing**\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "NumPy supports advanced indexing techniques such as boolean indexing and integer array indexing for flexible data access.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Example:**"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "PqIGpf8NyT8k"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": [
        "# Boolean indexing\n",
        "bool_mask = array_2d > 2\n",
        "print(array_2d[bool_mask])  # Output: [3, 4]\n",
        "\n",
        "# Integer indexing\n",
        "indices = [0, 1]\n",
        "print(array_2d[indices, indices])  # Output: [1, 4]\n"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "colab": {
          "base_uri": "https://localhost:8080/"

        }

    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "**10. Applications of Multidimensional Arrays**\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- Scientific Computing: Representing matrices, tensors, and multidimensional data.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- Machine Learning: Storing datasets, images, and model weights.\n",

      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "**16.What is the role of Bokeh in data visualization?**"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "YlxkM-bfyyYD"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "**Role of Bokeh in Data Visualization**\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "Bokeh is a powerful and interactive data visualization library for Python that enables the creation of visually appealing, highly interactive, and scalable plots and dashboards. Unlike static plotting libraries like Matplotlib, Bokeh is specifically designed for interactive visualizations that can be embedded in web applications. It is used extensively for creating interactive visualizations in real-time and for integrating data into interactive web-based platforms.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "**Key Features and Benefits of Bokeh**\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "1. Interactive Visualizations\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "Bokeh shines in creating interactive visualizations. Users can zoom, pan, hover over points, and update visualizations in real-time, making it highly suited for exploratory data analysis.\n",
        "\n",
        "- Zooming and Panning: Users can zoom into specific parts of the plot or pan across the data.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- Hover Tool: Display additional information when hovering over data points, which is particularly useful for large datasets.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "**2. High-Quality and Customizable Visuals**\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "Bokeh allows the creation of publication-quality graphics, with extensive options for customizing the appearance and style of plots (colors, fonts, axes, labels, etc.).\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- Custom styling, interactive widgets, and the ability to control aspects like layout and colors.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- Suitable for detailed and aesthetically pleasing plots that are highly customizable.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "**3. Web-Ready and Web Integration**\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "Bokeh visualizations are designed to be rendered in modern web browsers using HTML and JavaScript. The visualizations can be embedded directly into web applications, making them ideal for building dashboards.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- Embedding in Web Pages: Bokeh visualizations are compatible with frameworks like Flask, Django, and other web technologies, making it ideal for web-based dashboards.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- Real-time Data: Easily integrate real-time data sources to update plots dynamically.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "**4. Support for Complex Visualizations**\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "Bokeh supports a wide variety of plot types, including:\n",
        "\n",
        "- Line, scatter, bar, and heatmaps.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- Geographic maps (using tile sources like Google Maps or OpenStreetMap).\n",
        "Network graphs and 3D visualizations.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- Bokehâ€™s versatility enables the creation of complex visualizations such as network graphs and geospatial maps, which are difficult to implement with simpler libraries.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "**5. Large Data Handling**\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "Bokeh is optimized for handling large datasets by supporting efficient rendering techniques like WebGL. This allows the visualization of large-scale data without performance degradation, even in real-time applications.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- Bokeh uses WebGL for fast rendering of large numbers of data points.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- The ability to work with datasets that may not fit entirely in memory is useful for data streaming or high-volume analysis.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "**6. Integration with Other Tools**\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "Bokeh integrates well with other Python libraries, such as Pandas, NumPy, and Matplotlib, as well as tools for machine learning and statistical analysis.\n",
        "\n",
        "- Pandas Integration: Directly visualize Pandas DataFrames, making it easy to move from data processing to visualization.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- Jupyter Notebooks: Seamlessly integrate into Jupyter Notebooks for interactive data analysis.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "**7. Dashboards and Widgets**\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "Bokeh can be used to build interactive dashboards with sliders, buttons, dropdowns, and other widgets. It allows the creation of dynamic and interactive user interfaces to control the visualizations.\n",
        "\n",
        "- Widgets: Control elements like sliders, buttons, and text inputs allow users to interact with the data and update the plots.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- Layout: Flexible layout options (such as grid plots and tiled layouts) allow users to organize multiple visualizations within a single interface.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "**8. Easy-to-Use Python API**\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "While Bokeh visualizations are rendered in JavaScript, it provides an easy-to-use Python API for Python users, making it simple to create interactive plots without deep knowledge of JavaScript.\n",
        "\n",
        "- The Python interface allows users to specify plotting elements in a familiar, concise syntax.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "**Common Use Cases for Bokeh**\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "1.Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA)\n",
        "\n",
        "- Ideal for quickly exploring and interacting with datasets to identify trends, correlations, and patterns.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "2.Dashboards\n",
        "\n",
        "- Building interactive data dashboards that can be shared and embedded into web applications.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "3.Real-Time Data Visualization\n",
        "\n",
        "- Perfect for visualizing and updating live data streams, such as sensor data, financial data, or social media feeds.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "4.Geospatial Data Visualization\n",
        "\n",
        "- Displaying geographical maps and visualizing geospatial data with overlaid information, such as markers or heatmaps.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "5.Scientific Visualization\n",
        "\n",
        "- Displaying scientific or experimental data in interactive and publication-quality graphics, especially for large datasets or 3D visualizations.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "\n"

    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "**17. Explain the difference between apply() and map() in Pandas?**"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "HOivwuUS0nI6"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "In Pandas, both apply() and map() are used to apply functions to data, but they differ in their functionality and the types of objects they work with. Here's an overview of their differences:\n",
        "\n",
        "**1. map():**\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- Applies element-wise functions: map() is used to apply a function element-wise (i.e., to each individual element) to a Series.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- Works only on Series: map() is specifically designed for Series objects, meaning it cannot be directly used on DataFrames.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- Simple mappings: It's particularly useful for applying simple functions like replacing values, mapping values from a dictionary, or using lambda functions on a single column of data.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- Returns a Series: The result of map() is always a new Series.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "Usage:\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- Replacing or transforming values in a Series.\n",
        "\n",
        "- Using a dictionary or function to map each value in the Series.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "**Example:**"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "_jRjWO0w01oQ"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": [
        "import pandas as pd\n",
        "\n",
        "# Sample Series\n",
        "data = pd.Series([1, 2, 3, 4, 5])\n",
        "\n",
        "# Apply a function to each element (square each number)\n",
        "result = data.map(lambda x: x ** 2)\n",
        "print(result)\n",
        "\n",
        "# Using a dictionary to map values\n",
        "mapping_dict = {1: 'one', 2: 'two', 3: 'three'}\n",
        "result = data.map(mapping_dict)\n",
        "print(result)\n"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "colab": {
          "base_uri": "https://localhost:8080/"
        },
        "id": "aepEWdCgycW0",
        "outputId": "b77c38ce-a4df-4a19-ae90-e453261d0f38"
      },
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": [
        {
          "output_type": "stream",
          "name": "stdout",
          "text": [
            "0     1\n",
            "1     4\n",
            "2     9\n",
            "3    16\n",
            "4    25\n",
            "dtype: int64\n",
            "0      one\n",
            "1      two\n",
            "2    three\n",
            "3      NaN\n",
            "4      NaN\n",
            "dtype: object\n"
          ]
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "**2. apply():**\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- Applies a function along any axis: apply() can be used on both Series and DataFrames. It applies a function along an axis (rows or columns) in a DataFrame, or element-wise in a Series.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- Works on DataFrame and Series: apply() is more flexible than map() as it works on both Series and DataFrames, allowing you to apply functions across columns, rows, or elements.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- Can return various types: The result of apply() can be a Series, DataFrame, or even a scalar, depending on the function applied.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "**Usage:**\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- Series: Element-wise function application, similar to map().\n",
        "\n",
        "- DataFrame: Apply functions across rows or columns.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "**Example:**"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "9CSM43Wn5zOi"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": [
        "import pandas as pd\n",
        "\n",
        "# Sample DataFrame\n",
        "df = pd.DataFrame({\n",
        "    'A': [1, 2, 3],\n",
        "    'B': [4, 5, 6]\n",
        "})\n",
        "\n",
        "# Apply a function to each element of a Series\n",
        "result = df['A'].apply(lambda x: x + 2)\n",
        "print(result)\n",
        "\n",
        "# Apply a function across columns in a DataFrame\n",
        "result = df.apply(lambda x: x.max(), axis=0)  # Max of each column\n",
        "print(result)\n",
        "\n",
        "# Apply a function across rows in a DataFrame\n",
        "result = df.apply(lambda x: x.sum(), axis=1)  # Sum of each row\n",
        "print(result)\n"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "colab": {
          "base_uri": "https://localhost:8080/"
        },
        "id": "jMasamfz1HhT",
        "outputId": "5cdfbfb4-af5a-4bb3-bd8c-c980d3180a45"
      },
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": [
        {
          "output_type": "stream",
          "name": "stdout",
          "text": [
            "0    3\n",
            "1    4\n",
            "2    5\n",
            "Name: A, dtype: int64\n",
            "A    3\n",
            "B    6\n",
            "dtype: int64\n",
            "0    5\n",
            "1    7\n",
            "2    9\n",
            "dtype: int64\n"
          ]
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "**18. What are some advanced features of NumPy?**"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "KaLyvc766gDt"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "NumPy is a powerful library that provides numerous features to handle and manipulate large datasets efficiently. Beyond its basic functionality, NumPy also includes several advanced features that enable high-performance computations, sophisticated array manipulations, and efficient memory handling.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "**Here's an overview of some of these advanced features:**\n",
        "\n",
        "**1. Broadcasting**\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "Broadcasting is a feature that allows NumPy to perform arithmetic operations on arrays of different shapes without explicitly replicating the data in memory. It automatically adjusts the shapes of arrays during operations to make them compatible.\n",
        "\n",
        "Example:"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "BkEvVsoA6uvs"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": [
        "import numpy as np\n",
        "\n",
        "# Broadcasting example: Adding a scalar to an array\n",
        "arr = np.array([1, 2, 3])\n",
        "result = arr + 5  # Broadcasting the scalar 5 to each element\n",
        "print(result)  # Output: [6 7 8]\n",
        "\n",
        "# Broadcasting with different shapes\n",
        "arr_2d = np.array([[1, 2], [3, 4]])\n",
        "arr_1d = np.array([10, 20])\n",
        "result = arr_2d + arr_1d  # Broadcasting arr_1d across rows of arr_2d\n",
        "print(result)  # Output: [[11 22] [13 24]]\n"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "colab": {
          "base_uri": "https://localhost:8080/"
        },
        "id": "bB_Z7w896Kbk",
        "outputId": "012a88ce-94bd-4f53-c0d6-d4b7e706addf"
      },
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": [
        {
          "output_type": "stream",
          "name": "stdout",
          "text": [
            "[6 7 8]\n",
            "[[11 22]\n",
            " [13 24]]\n"
          ]
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "**2. Fancy Indexing (Advanced Indexing)**\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "Fancy indexing allows for more advanced selection techniques beyond basic slicing. You can use arrays or lists of indices to select or modify multiple array elements simultaneously.\n",
        "\n",
        "Example:\n"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "TlbWT2Q07BKD"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": [
        "import numpy as np\n",
        "\n",
        "arr = np.array([1, 2, 3, 4, 5])\n",
        "\n",
        "# Fancy indexing: selecting specific elements\n",
        "indices = [0, 2, 4]\n",
        "print(arr[indices])  # Output: [1 3 5]\n",
        "\n",
        "# Fancy indexing for multidimensional arrays\n",
        "arr_2d = np.array([[1, 2], [3, 4], [5, 6]])\n",
        "print(arr_2d[[0, 2], [1, 0]])  # Output: [2 5]\n"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "colab": {
          "base_uri": "https://localhost:8080/"

            "[1 3 5]\n",
            "[2 5]\n"
          ]
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "**3. Memory Management: Views and Copies**\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "NumPy provides efficient memory management through views and copies. A view is a new array that references the original data, while a copy is a completely new array with a separate memory allocation.\n",
        "\n",
        "- Views: More memory-efficient, as the data is shared.\n",
        "- Copies: Create independent arrays that don't share data.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "Example:"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "k4w33vn17RoB"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": [
        "arr = np.array([1, 2, 3, 4, 5])\n",
        "\n",
        "# View of the original array\n",
        "view = arr[1:4]\n",
        "view[0] = 99  # Modifies the original array\n",
        "print(arr)  # Output: [ 1 99  3  4  5]\n",
        "\n",
        "# Copy of the original array\n",
        "copy = arr[1:4].copy()\n",
        "copy[0] = 100  # Does not affect the original array\n",
        "print(arr)  # Output: [ 1 99  3  4  5]\n"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "colab": {
          "base_uri": "https://localhost:8080/"
        },
        "id": "LBKMH9zw7MRY",
        "outputId": "3da8a8fc-3d10-4bec-b480-b288d97e7224"
      },
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": [
        {
          "output_type": "stream",
          "name": "stdout",
          "text": [
            "[ 1 99  3  4  5]\n",
            "[ 1 99  3  4  5]\n"
          ]
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "**4. Stride Tricks**\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "Strides allow you to access arrays in a more memory-efficient way by specifying the step size between elements. This enables you to manipulate multidimensional arrays in advanced ways without creating new arrays.\n",
        "\n",
        "Example:"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "Z6cYbBgV7d_k"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": [
        "import numpy as np\n",
        "\n",
        "# Creating a strided array\n",
        "arr = np.arange(10)\n",
        "strided_arr = np.lib.stride_tricks.as_strided(arr, shape=(5, 2), strides=(8, 4))\n",
        "print(strided_arr)\n"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "colab": {
          "base_uri": "https://localhost:8080/"

      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "**5. Linear Algebra Functions**\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "NumPy includes a robust set of linear algebra functions, allowing you to perform matrix operations, such as dot products, matrix inversion, eigenvalue decomposition, singular value decomposition (SVD), etc.\n",
        "\n",
        "Example:"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "7Ul1-xHZ7rrG"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": [
        "import numpy as np\n",
        "\n",
        "# Matrix multiplication (Dot product)\n",
        "A = np.array([[1, 2], [3, 4]])\n",
        "B = np.array([[5, 6], [7, 8]])\n",
        "result = np.dot(A, B)\n",
        "print(result)  # Output: [[19 22] [43 50]]\n",
        "\n",
        "# Matrix inversion\n",
        "inv_A = np.linalg.inv(A)\n",
        "print(inv_A)  # Output: [[-2.  1.] [ 1.5 -0.5]]\n",
        "\n",
        "# Eigenvalue decomposition\n",
        "eigvals, eigvecs = np.linalg.eig(A)\n",
        "print(eigvals)  # Output: Eigenvalues of matrix A\n",
        "print(eigvecs)  # Output: Eigenvectors of matrix A\n"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "colab": {
          "base_uri": "https://localhost:8080/"
        },
        "id": "5II7H28T7k8G",
        "outputId": "d5a4fca0-60cc-40ea-b640-48bf8f1238b6"
      },
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": [
        {
          "output_type": "stream",
          "name": "stdout",
          "text": [
            "[[19 22]\n",
            " [43 50]]\n",
            "[[-2.   1. ]\n",
            " [ 1.5 -0.5]]\n",
            "[-0.37228132  5.37228132]\n",
            "[[-0.82456484 -0.41597356]\n",

        "\n",
