      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "**7. Vectorization and Universal Functions (ufuncs)**\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "NumPy's ufuncs (universal functions) allow for element-wise operations on arrays without the need for explicit Python loops. This enables high-performance computation by performing operations in compiled C code.\n",
        "\n",
        "Example:"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "EWM67RZC8CQH"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": [
        "import numpy as np\n",
        "\n",
        "# Element-wise square root operation\n",
        "arr = np.array([1, 4, 9, 16])\n",
        "sqrt_arr = np.sqrt(arr)\n",
        "print(sqrt_arr)  # Output: [1. 2. 3. 4.]\n",
        "\n",
        "# Element-wise addition\n",
        "arr1 = np.array([1, 2, 3])\n",
        "arr2 = np.array([4, 5, 6])\n",
        "sum_arr = np.add(arr1, arr2)\n",
        "print(sum_arr)  # Output: [5 7 9]\n"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "colab": {
          "base_uri": "https://localhost:8080/"
        },
        "id": "9UOyz6-Z78z6",
        "outputId": "caad6748-ee47-46e7-9e49-7dfa660d1351"
      },
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": [
        {
          "output_type": "stream",
          "name": "stdout",
          "text": [
            "[1. 2. 3. 4.]\n",
            "[5 7 9]\n"
          ]
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "**8. Multi-threading and Parallelism**\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "NumPy utilizes multi-threading to speed up computations for large datasets. Many operations are optimized to use multiple CPU cores, which is especially useful in data-intensive tasks.\n",
        "\n",
        "- Operations like matrix multiplication and dot products are optimized to run faster on multiple threads.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "**9. Aggregation and Reduction Operations**\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "NumPy provides various aggregation functions that operate on arrays along specified axes. These functions, such as sum(), mean(), std(), min(), max(), etc., can perform operations over rows or columns in a DataFrame or across dimensions in a multi-dimensional array.\n",
        "\n",
        "Example:"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "83bc_BhN8NYf"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": [
        "import numpy as np\n",
        "\n",
        "# Aggregation functions\n",
        "arr = np.array([[1, 2, 3], [4, 5, 6]])\n",
        "\n",
        "# Sum along rows\n",
        "sum_rows = np.sum(arr, axis=1)\n",
        "print(sum_rows)  # Output: [ 6 15]\n",
        "\n",
        "# Sum along columns\n",
        "sum_cols = np.sum(arr, axis=0)\n",
        "print(sum_cols)  # Output: [5 7 9]\n"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "colab": {
          "base_uri": "https://localhost:8080/"
        },
        "id": "2nfhp5TQ8HpR",
        "outputId": "5e8a3f55-3b06-4091-cb92-f61bee38c107"
      },
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": [
        {
          "output_type": "stream",
          "name": "stdout",
          "text": [
            "[ 6 15]\n",
            "[5 7 9]\n"
          ]
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "**10. Advanced Sorting and Searching**\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "NumPy includes efficient sorting and searching capabilities, including sorting by multiple keys, finding the nth largest/smallest values, and searching for specific values in arrays.\n",
        "\n",
        "Example:"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "WP89PyOE8cUN"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": [
        "import numpy as np\n",
        "\n",
        "# Sorting array\n",
        "arr = np.array([3, 1, 4, 1, 5, 9, 2])\n",
        "sorted_arr = np.sort(arr)\n",
        "print(sorted_arr)  # Output: [1 1 2 3 4 5 9]\n",
        "\n",
        "# Finding the indices of sorted values\n",
        "sorted_indices = np.argsort(arr)\n",
        "print(sorted_indices)  # Output: [1 3 6 0 2 4 5]\n",
        "\n",
        "# Searching for a value\n",
        "index = np.where(arr == 5)\n",
        "print(index)  # Output: (array([4]),)\n"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "colab": {
          "base_uri": "https://localhost:8080/"
        },
        "id": "CC2acBA58Xr4",
        "outputId": "7fb6997b-a504-436d-fa06-bb22732e05ac"
      },
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": [
        {
          "output_type": "stream",
          "name": "stdout",
          "text": [
            "[1 1 2 3 4 5 9]\n",
            "[1 3 6 0 2 4 5]\n",
            "(array([4]),)\n"

      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "Pandas simplifies time series analysis by providing a rich set of tools and methods designed specifically to handle time-indexed data efficiently and intuitively. Hereâ€™s how Pandas makes working with time series easier:\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "**1. Flexible Date and Time Handling**\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- Datetime Index: Pandas allows you to use DatetimeIndex for indexing, making time-based slicing, selection, and alignment straightforward.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- Conversion Tools: Functions like pd.to_datetime automatically convert strings or numbers into datetime objects.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- Custom Frequencies: Supports custom time intervals (e.g., daily, monthly, yearly) using frequency strings ('D', 'M', 'Y', etc.).\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "**2. Time-Based Indexing and Slicing**\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- You can index data using specific timestamps or ranges of dates. For example:\n"

      "source": [
        "import pandas as pd\n",
        "import numpy as np\n",
        "\n",
        "# Create a time series\n",
        "dates = pd.date_range('2025-01-01', periods=10, freq='D')\n",
        "data = np.random.randn(10)\n",
        "ts = pd.Series(data, index=dates)\n",
        "\n",
        "# Resample to monthly frequency\n",
        "monthly_mean = ts.resample('M').mean()\n",
        "\n",
        "# Compute rolling average\n",
        "rolling_avg = ts.rolling(window=3).mean()\n",
        "\n",
        "# Plot the time series and rolling average\n",
        "ts.plot(label='Original')\n",
        "rolling_avg.plot(label='Rolling Avg', linestyle='--')\n"

      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "**20.What is the role of a pivot table in Pandas?**"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "1-UqyIWBGNjW"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "A pivot table in Pandas is a powerful tool used to summarize, organize, and analyze data, especially when working with large datasets. It allows you to transform data by aggregating and reshaping it, enabling easier analysis and visualization. Hereâ€™s an overview of its role and functionality:\n",
        "\n",
        "**Key Roles of a Pivot Table in Pandas**\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "1.Data Summarization\n",
        "\n",
        "- A pivot table provides a concise summary of a dataset by aggregating data values based on specified row and column labels.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- Common aggregation functions include sum, mean, count, max, min, etc."
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "Td5vnybkGhSo"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": [
        "pivot_table = pd.pivot_table(data, values='sales', index='region', columns='product', aggfunc='sum')\n"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "colab": {

        "**Pandas Pivot Table vs. Excel Pivot Table**\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "Similarities:\n",

        "\n",
        "- Both allow dynamic data summarization and analysis.\n",
        "\n",

        "- Both support multi-dimensional data grouping and custom aggregation.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "Advantages in Pandas:\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- More control through Python programming.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- Easy integration with data preprocessing, cleaning, and visualization workflows.\n"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "GfHqDegAIf1G"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "**21.Why is NumPyâ€™s array slicing faster than Pythonâ€™s list slicing?**"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "hNPWT2w9IrZv"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "NumPy's array slicing is faster than Python's list slicing due to several reasons tied to the underlying design and implementation of NumPy arrays compared to Python lists. Here's a breakdown:\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "**1. Homogeneous Data Type**\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "-  NumPy Array: Arrays are homogeneous, meaning all elements are of the same data type (e.g., integers, floats). This allows for efficient memory storage and faster operations because the data can be stored in a contiguous block of memory.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- Python List: Lists are heterogeneous, meaning they can contain elements of different types. Each element is a reference to an object, which adds overhead during slicing.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "**2. Contiguous Memory Layout**\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- NumPy Array: NumPy arrays are stored in a contiguous memory block, enabling highly efficient memory access and slicing. The array slicing operation simply computes the start, stop, and step indices and creates a new \"view\" without copying the data.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- Python List: Python lists are stored as an array of pointers to the actual objects, which are scattered in memory. Slicing a list creates a new list and involves copying the references or the elements themselves, which is slower.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "**3. View vs. Copy**\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- NumPy Array: Slicing typically creates a \"view\" of the original data, meaning no new data is copied unless explicitly needed. This minimizes memory usage and speeds up operations.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- Python List: Slicing a list creates a new list object with a copy of the selected elements, which takes additional time and memory.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "**4. Optimized C Implementation**\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- NumPy Array: NumPy is implemented in C, and many of its operations, including slicing, are optimized using low-level C routines. This ensures faster execution compared to Python's built-in list slicing.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- Python List: Python lists are implemented at a higher level, leading to more overhead.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "**5. Broadcasting and Strides**\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- NumPy Array: NumPy uses strides (step sizes) to efficiently calculate the position of elements in memory. This makes slicing and accessing subarrays computationally efficient.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- Python List: Slicing involves iterating over the indices and copying elements one by one, which is slower.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "**Performance Comparison**\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "Hereâ€™s a practical demonstration of the speed difference:\n",
        "\n"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "SRwo1wMGI6ks"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": [
        "import numpy as np\n",
        "import time\n",
        "\n",
        "# Create a large NumPy array and Python list\n",
        "np_array = np.arange(1_000_000)\n",
        "py_list = list(range(1_000_000))\n",
        "\n",
        "# Measure slicing time for NumPy array\n",
        "start = time.time()\n",
        "_ = np_array[100:900_000]\n",
        "np_time = time.time() - start\n",
        "\n",
        "# Measure slicing time for Python list\n",
        "start = time.time()\n",
        "_ = py_list[100:900_000]\n",
        "list_time = time.time() - start\n",
        "\n",
        "print(f\"NumPy slicing time: {np_time:.6f} seconds\")\n",
        "print(f\"Python list slicing time: {list_time:.6f} seconds\")\n"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "colab": {
          "base_uri": "https://localhost:8080/"
        },
        "id": "oEbUMvujIcKm",
        "outputId": "4846b1b0-304b-42f5-af7a-443f3fd33b0a"
      },
      "execution_count": 13,
      "outputs": [
        {
          "output_type": "stream",
          "name": "stdout",
          "text": [
            "NumPy slicing time: 0.000293 seconds\n",
            "Python list slicing time: 0.010590 seconds\n"
          ]
        }
      ]
    },

        "**4. Analyzing Categorical Data**\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "Seaborn offers various plots to compare categorical data.\n",
        "\n",
        "**- Bar Plot**"

      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "**4.How do you calculate the correlation matrix using Seaborn and visualize it with a heatmap?**"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "aAxNqYJ3RFku"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": [
        "import pandas as pd\n",
        "import seaborn as sns\n",
        "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
        "\n",
        "# Example DataFrame\n",
        "data = {\n",
        "    'A': [1, 2, 3, 4, 5],\n",
        "    'B': [5, 4, 3, 2, 1],\n",
        "    'C': [2, 3, 4, 5, 6],\n",
        "    'D': [10, 20, 30, 40, 50]\n",
        "}\n",
        "df = pd.DataFrame(data)\n",
        "\n",
        "# Calculate the correlation matrix\n",
        "corr_matrix = df.corr()\n",
        "\n",
        "# Visualize the correlation matrix with a heatmap\n",
        "plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))\n",
        "sns.heatmap(corr_matrix, annot=True, cmap='coolwarm', fmt='.2f', cbar=True)\n",
        "plt.title(\"Correlation Matrix Heatmap\")\n",
        "plt.show()\n"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "colab": {
          "base_uri": "https://localhost:8080/",
          "height": 549
        },
        "id": "JeTrFd3iQmtq",
        "outputId": "2ee6bbb4-ceb0-425d-931f-fb2d88114478"
      },
      "execution_count": 36,

          "output_type": "display_data",

    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "**5.Generate a bar plot using Plotly?**"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "Gv5xBMxiRZgu"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": [
        "import plotly.express as px\n",
        "\n",
        "# Example data\n",
        "data = {\n",
        "    'Category': ['A', 'B', 'C', 'D', 'E'],\n",
        "    'Values': [10, 15, 7, 12, 9]\n",
        "}\n",
        "\n",
        "# Create the bar plot\n",
        "fig = px.bar(\n",
        "    x=data['Category'],\n",
        "    y=data['Values'],\n",
        "    title=\"Example Bar Plot\",\n",
        "    labels={'x': 'Category', 'y': 'Values'},\n",
        "    color=data['Category'],  # Optional: Adds color to each bar\n",
        "    text=data['Values']  # Optional: Adds text annotations\n",
        ")\n",
        "\n",
        "# Customize the layout (optional)\n",
        "fig.update_layout(\n",
        "    xaxis_title=\"Category\",\n",
        "    yaxis_title=\"Values\",\n",
        "    showlegend=False\n",
        ")\n",
        "\n",
        "# Show the plot\n",
        "fig.show()\n"
      ],

        "**6. Create a DataFrame and add a new column based on an existing column?**"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "G7pScMhCR4BJ"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": [
        "import pandas as pd\n",
        "\n",
        "# Create a DataFrame\n",
        "data = {\n",
        "    'Name': ['Alice', 'Bob', 'Charlie', 'David'],\n",
        "    'Age': [24, 27, 22, 32],\n",
        "    'Salary': [50000, 60000, 55000, 70000]\n",
        "}\n",
        "df = pd.DataFrame(data)\n",
        "\n",
        "# Add a new column based on an existing column\n",
        "# Example: Add a column for tax (10% of Salary)\n",
        "df['Tax'] = df['Salary'] * 0.1\n",
        "\n",
        "# Add another column categorizing age groups\n",
        "df['Age Group'] = df['Age'].apply(lambda x: 'Young' if x < 25 else 'Adult')\n",
        "\n",
        "# Display the updated DataFrame\n",
        "print(df)\n"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "colab": {
          "base_uri": "https://localhost:8080/"
        },
        "id": "MuLm4Tv1RxdG",
        "outputId": "d0cab398-4dc1-44b3-e06c-0a0807e861d6"
      },
      "execution_count": 38,
      "outputs": [
        {
          "output_type": "stream",

        "# Example data\n",

        "y1 = [0, 1, 4, 9, 16, 25]  # First line (y = x^2)\n",
        "y2 = [0, 1, 8, 27, 64, 125]  # Second line (y = x^3)\n",
        "\n",
        "# Create the plot\n",
        "plt.plot(x, y1, label=\"y = x^2\", marker='o', linestyle='-', color='blue')\n",
        "plt.plot(x, y2, label=\"y = x^3\", marker='s', linestyle='--', color='red')\n",
        "\n",
        "# Add titles and labels\n",

        "plt.xlabel(\"X-axis\")\n",
        "plt.ylabel(\"Y-axis\")\n",
        "\n",
        "# Add a legend\n",
        "plt.legend()\n",
        "\n",
        "# Show gridlines (optional)\n",

        "# Display the plot\n",
        "plt.show()\n"

      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": [
        "import pandas as pd\n",
        "\n",
        "# Create a DataFrame\n",
        "data = {\n",
        "    'Name': ['Alice', 'Bob', 'Charlie', 'David'],\n",
        "    'Age': [24, 27, 22, 32],\n",
        "    'Salary': [50000, 60000, 55000, 70000]\n",
        "}\n",
        "df = pd.DataFrame(data)\n",
        "\n",
        "# Define the threshold\n",
        "threshold = 25\n",
        "\n",
        "# Filter rows where 'Age' is greater than the threshold\n",
        "filtered_df = df[df['Age'] > threshold]\n",
        "\n",
        "# Display the original and filtered DataFrame\n",
        "print(\"Original DataFrame:\")\n",
        "print(df)\n",
        "print(\"\\nFiltered DataFrame (Age > 25):\")\n",
        "print(filtered_df)\n"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "colab": {
          "base_uri": "https://localhost:8080/"
        },
        "id": "Q_se2v1TSlaO",
        "outputId": "a308761d-431c-4678-bc46-bf2b1926d0df"
      },
      "execution_count": 41,
      "outputs": [
        {
          "output_type": "stream",
          "name": "stdout",
          "text": [
            "Original DataFrame:\n",
            "      Name  Age  Salary\n",
            "0    Alice   24   50000\n",
            "1      Bob   27   60000\n",
            "2  Charlie   22   55000\n",
            "3    David   32   70000\n",
            "\n",
            "Filtered DataFrame (Age > 25):\n",
            "    Name  Age  Salary\n",
            "1    Bob   27   60000\n",
